    <h2>The Legacy of ARPANET</h2>

    <p>
      Though ARPANET was initially a project for the U.S. military and academic
      researchers, its legacy has had a profound impact on the development of
      the modern internet. The shift from centralized communication methods to
      decentralized networks-along with innovations like packet switching and
      the TCP/IP protocol-formed the backbone of the internet.
    </p>

    <p>
      In 1990, ARPANET was officially decommissioned, but by then, the internet
      had already begun its transformation into a global public network. The
      innovations pioneered by ARPANET researchers continue to shape how we
      connect, communicate, and share information online.
    </p>

    <p>
      ARPANET's influence is still felt today-from the protocols that underpin
      the World Wide Web to the decentralized structure of the modern internet,
      which allows billions of devices to communicate with each other. ARPANET,
      despite its humble beginnings, was the starting point of a technological
      revolution that continues to evolve at a rapid pace.
    </p>

